that you can do to all the wonder I will do.

Ice, little baby, don't you cry.
Mother and father are born to die.
I surrender, surrender, surrender, surrender, surrender, surrender, surrender, come in.
I surrender and open the door and let me come in.
I can't see much.
Born in 1844.
Huh?
My name is Wallace Quarterman, in and through the state of Georgia.
The morning I was shooting breakfast in the house, and the big gun shot to portray us.
The big gun shot, so I buy a kind of breakfast in the house.
The overseer asked me, what is that if that is thunder?
I tell him, I don't know.
I know what the answer is.
And so he shot three times, and he commenced to shoot.
until the plate commenced to rattle on the table.
And he called me and told me to run down in the field and tell Peter to turn the people loose that the Yankees come.
And so I run down in the field and hooped and hollered at him, Peter, and told him, Mr. Giggo said turn the people loose because the Yankees come.
Who was Peter?
The driver.
And so he said that, uh,
Wallace was lying when he said so.
When he said so, then the Yankee beat to the land and they drowned.
You understand, way down south, getting mighty poor.
Kids, they used to drink coffee, but now they're drinking rye.
They said, let's raise a uniband, make the rebel understand to leave our land for the sake of Uncle Sam.
Way down south, getting mighty poor, shut out the wildcat and see the rebel run.
I ain't gonna end up with them team again.
I've been over all of them.
Yes.
And that, the people then throw where they go then.
They throw where they go, and they call we all up, you know, and give you all freedom, because we are this much as free as them.
Now you understand.
But the Yankee thing must go back to the South to help me.
Well, they didn't.
Of course, there was so much doubt.
And thinking the way, they would have done more.
But there's so much doubt in the way.
They couldn't because the colored people should have been poor.
And some white people should have been poor too.
You understand?
And the reddish, that's them.
That's me.
I satisfy so far what the Lord has done for me.
I come through.
So all this has been up and down through the militia.
Well, tell me about how they went to Hawkinsville and drove the sword down in the ground.
He told them.
They know you.
After they said you can go free,
Then what did you do?
Did you run on off the plantation that day?
Did you leave the plantation that day after they told you to go free?
Well, the mortars promised to give me $40 a month in rent.
Well, lots of the boys said they ain't want it.
They'd rather go free, you know.
Well, of course, by I have built, you understand, I get along with them, you know.
Eat right out the big pot, you know.
And after they sold down
sword down, they just make them sword down and they just get on the sword and squash them down.
You go in Hawkinsville and you see all the swords down now in the ground.
And after the sword was down, there's tension and then south tension.
And after the south tension, then they play.
Yes, play the one foot one way, one foot the other way, one foot all the way around.
What about afterwards, you know, when the Scottish people had the jail and everything?
Tell us about that.
Yeah, that's me.
Everything's been in me hands.
But they couldn't control the colored people.
They do so much mischief and tell me after going back to the white people, we had education.
You know, when a man ain't got no education, he ain't got no thing.
All we tried to show them, they wouldn't take this, kill one another and join us.
So we had to nominate Democrats over the head.
They didn't like it.
Many got killed by nominating the Democrats, but we couldn't help it to stop them so much killing.
You understand?
So we nominated the Democrats and we had a big time from that till now.
The time ain't bad, because it's been then.
Because a man thinks nothing of killing a man and taking a drink of water.
But since we nominate the Democrats, we have more insurance, you understand?
The law come in possession then, you know, they wouldn't hear it, the colored people.
Told, mama, told.
Yes, that's the way they come in possession.
But we had our own lawyers, judges and everything, where they just would run everything in the dust, you know, kill everything, couldn't stand it.
Well, did you ever have an office?
Did you ever hold an office?
I would want an office.
Oh, yeah.
Now, man, I wouldn't want an office for an officer, an unjust kind of thing.
You understand?
You've got to go and please that fellow, you know.
You've got to stop doing what God tells you and go and please that fellow.
And the right way will you rap out.
What's becoming your old master?
Old master?
He died in the Yadda fever.
He was a nice man to me.
I wouldn't take anything from him.
What was his name?
Colonel Fedvary.
Fred Berry.
Yes, he was a kind of.
I wouldn't take anything, but me and him was just like one, you know.
Yes.
Yes, ma'am.
Well, where was his plantation?
His plantation on Savannah River.
You know, Killeby Island.
Mm-hmm.
You know, Chatham County, you know, Savannah.
Yes.
On Killeby Island.
Mm-hmm.
Yeah.
Yes.
I wouldn't take nothing from him.
Well, did the white folks like his willingness?
And you all were in power?
Oh, they liked me.
They would like me all the way, because I would text them, you know.
I would text them, I would hold it.
I would hold it, yanking myself, and then destroy them, you know.
You see, I just didn't understand how to speak, you know.
Tell another, you know.
I see a man going to do a wrong thing, I'd show something.
I'd stop him.
Well, did the white people, did your mouth and all them like to see the Negroes be the judge in the jail and everything?
No, you see, according to law, you know.
You don't mind you be that way if you know what you're doing.
Don't you see?
Yeah.
You see, they don't know what they're doing.
And they prove that they
This is AFS recording number 9,990 of original LWO number 1500.
This is reel number three of three.
Talk to who?
Well, just tell me what your name is.
My name is Fountain Hughes.
I was born in Charlottesville, Virginia.
My grandfather belonged to Thomas Jefferson.
My grandfather was 115 years old when he died.
And now I am 101 years old.
That's enough.
But what she made, I don't know.
I never asked her.
You just go ahead and talk away there.
You don't mind, do you, Uncle Sam?
No.
And when now your husband and you both are young, you all try to live like young people ought to live.
Don't want everything somebody else has got.
Whatever you get, it is human.
Be satisfied.
And don't spend your money until you get it.
So many people get in debt.
Well, oh, it's so cheap and I bought it.
You spend your money before you get it because you're going in debt for what you want.
When you want something, wait until you get the money and pay for it cash.
That's what I've done.
If I wanted anything, I'd wait until I got the money and I paid for it cash.
I never bought nothing on time in my life.
Now, plenty of people, if they want a suit of clothes, they go to work and they buy them on time.
Well, they say it was cheap.
If you got the money, you can buy them cheaper.
They want something for waiting on you until you get ready to pay them.
And if you got the money, you can go where you choose and buy it when you want it.
See?
Don't buy it because somebody else go down and run a debt and run a bill or I'm going to run it too.
Don't do that.
I never done it.
Now, I'm 100 years old, and I don't owe nobody five cents.
I ain't got no money either.
I'm just as happy as somebody that's got a million.
Nothing worries me.
My head ain't even white.
Nothing in the world worries me.
I can sit here in this house till night.
Nobody can come and say, Mr. Hughes, you owe me a quarter, you owe me a dollar, you owe me five cents.
No, you can't.
I don't owe you nothing.
Why?
I never made no bills in my life.
And I'm living, too.
And I'm 100 years old.
And if you take my advice today, you'll never make a bill.
Of course, what you want, give me money to pay in cash.
And then the rest of the money is yours.
But here on the bill, they... Well, so much and so much, and you don't have to pay.
Nothing down.
When you come to pay, it's all...
You have to pay no more.
But they'll charge you more.
They're getting something out of you, else they wouldn't trust you.
But I can't just say what they're getting.
But they're getting something out of you, else they wouldn't want your credit.
Now, I tell you that.
Anybody that trusts you for $2 or half a count with them by the month or by the week, store count or any count, they're getting something out of you.
Else they don't want to accommodate you that much to trust you.
Now, if I want, of course, I ain't got no clothes, but if I want some clothes, if I ain't got no money, I'm going to wait until I get the money to buy them.
I'm not going to say, of course, I can get them on the church.
I go down and get them.
I got to pay a dollar more anyhow.
You're either going to charge them or what you said, taxes or so much.
But if I got the money to pay cash, I pay the taxes and all down cash, then it's all done with.
So many colored people, head over heels in debt.
Trust me, trust me.
I get it on time.
So I want a set of furniture.
But I don't pay down so much and rest on time.
You don't pay it for them then.
When you pay down so much, you may charge $50, $100 for a set, and you pay down $25 cash.
You don't pay it for them.
That's all it was worth, $25.
Now I'm $75 in debt now.
Of course, I have to pay $100, that's it.
And it's only worth about $25.
But you bind on time.
But people ain't got sense enough to know it.
But when you get old like I am, you come in and you think, well, I have done wrong.
I should have kept my money until I wanted this thing, and when I wanted it,
I take my money and go cash cash, or else I do without it.
Suppose you want a new dress.
You say, well, I buy it, but I don't need it.
But I can get it on time.
Well, let's go down to the store today and get something on time.
Why don't you go down and get a dress on time, something else, and let him
I won't have to sell that to you on time.
You don't have to pay nothing down.
But there's a payday coming.
And when that payday comes, they want you to come pay them.
If you don't, they can't get no more.
Well, if you never do that, if you don't start it, you will never end it.
I never did buy nothing on time.
I must tell you on this, I'm sitting right here now today, and if it's the last word I've got to tell you,
I never even much as tried to buy a shirt on time.
And plenty of people go to work, down to the store and buy $3 and $4 for a shirt, $2, $3, $7, $8 for a pair of pants.
Of course, they get them on time.
I don't know, no, no.
I say, I've got, I buy some for $5.
What I got to $5, I'll pay for it.
I'm done with that.
You talk about how old you are, Uncle Fountain.
How far back do you remember?
I remember, well, I tell you, things come to me in spells, you know.
I remember things more when I'm laying down than I do when I'm standing, when I'm walking around.
Now, in my boy days, boys lived quite different from the way they live now.
But boys wasn't as mean as they are now either.
Boys lived to, they had a good time.
The masters didn't treat them bad.
And they were always satisfied.
They never wore no shoes until they were 12 or 13 years old.
Now people put on shoes on babies, you know, when they're two years old, when they're a month old, I don't know.
Put shoes on babies just as soon as you see them out in the street, they got shoes on.
I told a woman the other day, I said, I never had no shoes until I was 13 years old.
She said, well, but you bruised your feet all up and stumped your toes.
I said, yes, many times I've stumped my toes and blood run out of them.
That didn't make them buy me no shoes.
And I've been... Oh...
Oh, you wore a dress like a woman until I was 10, 12, 13 years old.
You wore a dress, Philip?
Yes, I didn't wear no pants because I didn't make boys' pants.
Boys wore dresses.
Now the women's wearing the dresses and the boys are going with the...
The women's wearing the pants now and the boys are wearing the dresses.
Who did you work for, Uncle Tom?
Who did I work for?
Yeah.
You mean when I was a slave?
Yeah, when you were a slave.
Who did you work for?
Well, I belonged to Burnish when I was a slave.
My mother belonged to Burnish.
But we was all slave children.
Soon after, when we found out that we were free,
Well, then we was bound out to different people.
Thicklin, Andrew, and Andrews, and all such people as that.
And we'd run away and wouldn't stay with them.
Well, then we'd just go and stay wherever we could, lay out all night, you know, anywhere.
We had no home, you know.
We just turned out like a lot of cattle.
You know how they turn cattle out in the pasture?
Well, after freedom, you know, colored people didn't have nothing.
Colored people didn't have no beds when they were slaves.
People slept on the floor.
Padded here and padded there.
Just like a lot of wild people, we didn't know nothing.
Didn't lie looking no book.
And there were some pre-born colored people where they had little education.
But there were very few of them where we was.
And we all had a, what you call, I might call it now,
jail sentence, just the same as we were in jail.
Now, I couldn't go from here across the street, or I couldn't go to nobody's house without having a note or something from my master.
And if I had that pass, that was what we called a pass, if I had that pass, I could go wherever he sent me, and I'd have to be back.
Whoever he sent me to, they'd give me another pass,
And I'd bring that back so as to show how long I'd been gone.
We couldn't go out and stay an hour or two hours or something like that.
They'd send you, you know, say, for instance, I'd go out to the shirtless place, I'd have to walk.
And I'd have to be back maybe an hour.
Maybe they'd give me an hour.
I don't know just how long they'd give me.
But they'd give me a note so there wasn't nobody in the field with me to tell who I belonged to.
And when I come back,
I'd carry it to my master and give that to him.
That'd be all right.
But I couldn't just walk away like the people just now, you know.
We were slaves.
We belonged to people.
They'd sell us, like they sell horses and cows and hogs and all like that, have an auction bench and put you up on the bench and beat on you the same as you're beating on cattle, you know.
Was that in Charlotte that you were a slave?
Was that in Charlotte?
Or Charlottesville.
That isn't Charlottesville.
Charlottesville, Virginia.
They'd sell to women, sell to men.
And then if they had any bad ones, they'd sell them to the nigger traders, what they called the nigger traders.
And they'd ship them down south.
They'd sell them down south.
But otherwise, if you were a good person, they wouldn't sell you.
But if you were bad, meaning they didn't want to beat you and knock you around,
They'd sell you to what's called a nigger trader.
They'd have a regular...
I was sold every month, you know, at the courthouse.
And then they'd sell you, maybe $200, $100, $500.
Were you ever sold from one person to another?
Were you ever sold?
No, I never was sold.
You always stayed with the same person?
I was too young to sell.
Oh, I see.
See, I wasn't old enough during the war to sell, during the army.
And my father got killed in the army, you know, so it left us small children just to live on whatever people choose to give us.
I would bind out for a dollar a month, and my mother used to collect the money.
Children couldn't spend money when I come along.
In fact,
When I come along, young men couldn't spend no money until they were 21 years old.
And then you're 21, well, then you could spend your money.
But if you wasn't 21, you couldn't spend no money.
I couldn't spend 10 cents if somebody gave it to me.
Of course, they'd think, well, you might have stole it.
We all come along, you might say, we had to give an account of what you'd done.
You couldn't just do things and walk off and say, I didn't do it.
We'd have to give an account of it.
Now, after we got freed and they turned us out like cattle, we didn't have nowhere to go.
We didn't have nobody to boss us.
And we didn't know nothing.
There wasn't no school.
And when they started the little school, the people that were slaves, many of them couldn't go to school.
Except they had a father and a mother.
And my father was dead and my mother was living.
But she had three, four other little children.
She had to put them all to work to help take care of the others.
So we had what you call worse than dogs have got it now.
Dogs have got it now better than we had it when we come along.
I know, I remember one night I was out after I was free and I didn't have nowhere to go.
I didn't have nowhere to sleep.
I didn't know what to do.
My brother and I was together.
So we knew a man that had a living stable there.
And we crept in that yard and got in one of the hacks like an automobile and slept in that hack all night long.
So next morning,
we could get out and go where we belonged.
But we were afraid to go at night because we didn't know where to go and didn't know what time to go.
But we had got away from there and we were afraid to go back.
So we kept sleeping in that thing all night until the next morning and we got back where we belonged before the people got up.
As soon as the day commenced to break, we got up and commenced to go where we belonged.
But we never done that but the one time.
After that, we...
If it was away, we'd try to get back before night come.
And that was on a Sunday, too, that we done that.
Now, when we were slaves, we couldn't do that, see?
And if we got free, we didn't know nothing to do.
My mother, she hunted places and bound us out for a dollar a month.
We stayed there maybe a couple of years.
She'd come over and collect the money every month.
And a dollar...
